# Whitelist for debride dead-code detection.
#
# Each entry below is a method name debride flags as dead, but we know is
# actually used through a Rails convention or framework mechanism that
# debride can't see. Every entry must have a comment explaining why.
#
# NOTE: the repo currently exceeds 50 findings even with `--rails`, so the
# code_quality:debride rake task uses a RATCHET approach: it records a
# baseline count in the task itself and fails only if the count increases.
# This whitelist is for *categories* we want to permanently suppress so
# the ratchet reflects true regressions rather than Rails noise.
#
# Format: one bare method name per line. Hash/octothorpe lines are comments.
# See: https://github.com/seattlerb/debride#whitelist

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# ActiveRecord has_many / belongs_to generated reader methods.
# debride sees `has_many :foo` and flags the generated `foo` reader.
# These are exercised by associations and tests — keep them.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
podcast_memberships
users
device_codes
oauth_access_grants
oauth_access_tokens
narration

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# ActiveJob#perform — called dynamically by the queue executor after
# perform_later enqueues the job. debride can't trace the dispatch.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
perform

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Controller actions dispatched via routes.rb.
#
# `debride --rails` uses naming heuristics (it does not parse routes.rb),
# so it misses many real endpoints. These are live actions invoked by the
# Rails router. Each name below is present in routes.rb.
#
# NOTE: debride whitelist entries match by bare method name (no class
# qualifier), so `show` silences every `#show` in the codebase. That is the
# desired behavior for Rails-convention action names — Phase 2 of the
# dead-code triage is the narrower per-method investigation.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
show
index
new
determine_layout
home
marketing_home
add_rss_feed
extension_help
cli_help
claude_code_help
claude_help
chatgpt_help
post_login_path
icons
handle
create_user
magic_link_token
inbound
stripe
oauth_authorization_server
oauth_protected_resource
authentication
mpp

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Rails framework dispatch hooks (ActionCable, ActionMailbox).
#
# - ApplicationCable::Connection#connect — invoked by the Rack cable mount
#   when a WebSocket client opens a connection.
# - Channel#subscribed — invoked when a client subscribes to a channel.
# - ActionMailbox::Base#process — invoked by the mailbox router when an
#   inbound email matches a routing rule.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
connect
subscribed
process
